headline: Nvidia set for $320 billion price swing after earnings, options indicate
summary: NEW YORK (Reuters) -Nvidia's earnings report on Wednesday could trigger a $320 billion swing in the chipmaker's market value — the largest post-earnings move ever ​for the AI giant — as investors seek signals about whether the artificial intelligence boom is accelerating or cooling.  Nvidia ‌options implied about a 7% move for the stock in either direction after it announces its quarterly results, which are expected following the market close on ‌Wednesday, data from analytics firm Option Research & Technology Services (ORATS) showed.  At Nvidia's current market value of about $4.6 trillion, the options-implied move would represent the largest one-day market value change following quarterly earnings for the artificial-intelligence bellwether, a Reuters analysis found.

headline: Wall Street's AI-driven surge put to test by Nvidia results
summary:
STORY: U.S. stocks started Tuesday in the red as concerns about lofty equity valuations intensified.

Megacap tech stocks led the decline including those of AI-related companies such as chip powerhouse Nvidia.

It reports earnings after the closing bell on Wednesday and the results are seen as a litmus test for the AI-driven rally that has pushed markets to record highs this year.

Market participants will be hanging on every word from CEO Jensen Huang on the company’s outlook, including Wedbush Securities Managing Director Dan Ives. 

“It's a Super Bowl for tech [stock] owners. Nvidia, the godfather of AI, Jensen [Huang] and that's the foundation of the AI revolution. We expect robust numbers that should demand accelerating not just for Nvidia chips, but overall demand of the AI revolution.”

One chief investment strategist tells Reuters that investors will be reviewing the results with a fine-tooth comb, looking for any sort of cracks and scrutinizing the guidance to see if this is the beginning of a potentially deeper problem.

Ives says he thinks investors are missing the larger picture.

“In my opinion, investors are underestimating the scale and scope of what this is going to look like with robotics, with autonomous, with the future.”

Ives dismisses talk of a bubble and says the bull market will continue for another two years.

headline: Market Talk: Nvidia will crush earnings, but will it matter?

Chipmaker Nvidia's results, expected on Wednesday after the market close, will be scrutinized for signs that the AI juggernaut, which has provided the muscle for much of the stock market's recent rally, has staying power.

Mahn expects Nvidia will exceed analysts' estimates for the quarter and perhaps "even guide higher in terms of their forecast for the next quarter and maybe even for 2026 overall" - signs that "the AI revolution is still alive and well."

"But I don't think all of that matters," he added. "I don't think it will meet the expectations of investors."
